express-session
	is a middleware use for store user session data on server side.
	session id is stored in cookie.
	
	1.installation
		npm i express-session
		
	2. create session middleware 
		const session = require('express-session');
		
		app.use(session({options))
	
		options:
			secret: '', 				//used to sign the session id cookie 
			resave: false, 				//dont save session if not modified.
			saveUninitialized: false,	//don't save empty sessions
			cookie:{
							
			}							//control cookie behavior 
			store :				//define where session data are stored (in-memory,Redis,MongoDB)
									by default in memory 
	3. set session value 
	
		req.session.user = { id: 1}
		
	4. get session value
		
		req.session.user
		
	5. destroy session 
	
		req.session.destroy((err)=>{
			if(err) return res.status(500).send('Error destroying session');
			
			res.clearCookie('connect.sid'); //optional but recommended.
			
			res.send("session destroyed. Logged out successfully")
		})
	-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
	session options:
	cookie:	{ 	path: '/', 
				httpOnly: true, 
				secure: false, 
				maxAge: null 
			}
			--these are default options
			
		-maxAge : 	number - default null	--time (in ms) until the cookie expires
					Ex- 1000 * 60 * 60 = 1hr
					
		-expires : 
		
		-secure : boolean - default false	--if true cookie is only sent only over https
		
		-httpOnly : default true : protects from XSS attacks 
						if false the cookie is visibe to client side javascript 
						any one can read it with console.log(document.cookie)
						
						XSS (cross site scripting) is a type of security vulnerability
		-path : default '/'  -- restricts cookies to a specific route path
		
		-sameSite  	--Controls cross-site sending (strict, lax, none)
	-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
	req.session
		To store or access session data
		
	Session.regenerate(callback): 
		create a brand-new session for the user — with a new session ID — while preserving or reassigning any necessary data
		
		req.session.regenerate(err => {
			if (err) throw err;
			
			req.session.user = { id: 1, name: 'Yuvraj' };
			res.send('Login successful');
		});
		
	Session.reload(callback):
		reload session data from store in case it has been updated
		
		req.session.reload(function (err) {
			if (err) throw err;
			// Session data is now reloaded
			console.log(req.session);
		});
	Session.save(callback):
		normally express-session automatically saves the session at end of the request (when the response is about to send)
		but some time you want to force to save like before redirecting...
		
